


Security
            * OAuth2 + JWT Bearer token
            * Never cache raw sensitive data (IBAN, card toke)
            * IBAN encrypted at rest and masked in API responses
            * Secrets managed in Vault / Kubernetes secrets

Cache:
            * As it handles sensitive data, I would analyse to see the impact of the cache use. Its better to lose a bit of performance here and garantee correctness.
            * Redis — cache payment method lists and contract assignments 
            * Key: payment_methods:{customerId} TTL: 5-10 min.
            * Invalidate on any write to that customer's methods.
            * Never cache raw sensitive fields (IBAN, tokens).

Fail Tolerance:
            * API Gateway:
                * We can have a rate limiter, to avoid charges too big at once
                * Circuit breaker: if the service is returning 500s, returns fast faliures instead of queuing requests
            * Service 
                * Circuit breaker in outbound calls: if PSP is down we store the token and try again later, without failing the payment info update. (Resilience4j)
                * Cache miss: don't allow a cache miss to return an error, go to db and get the data.
                * Idempotency keys on write endpoints to make client retries safe. 
            * Database
                * DB and outbox writes are atomic. No event os Kafka if the transaction fails
                * Read can be done on replica writes always go to primary. If writes are slow, read are not affected
            * Kafka + Outbox
                * Consumer offset commit only after successful call to SAP
                * No event published to Kafka without the guarantee that the DB write succeeded first.
                * Outbox sits with sent_at = NULL until broker is reachable.
                * SAP downtime never blocks customer-facing writes.
            * Payment Sync Worker
                * Exponential retries, and after max retries send to DLT for treatment. (Jitter)
                * Separate deployable, can work independently from the main service, doesn't break the flow if its down.
            * Health Checks and Multiple Instances
                * Have more than one instance and have synced with Kubernetes to restart failing instance

Tracebility
            * Audit Log
                * Append-only table, never updated or deleted
                * Written in same transaction as domain write
                * Stores before and after state as JSON
                * Records actor (customer/agent/system), timestamp, action and aggregate affected
                * Used for: billing disputes, GDPR requests, regulatory audits
            * Contract-Payment-Method-History table
                * Append only
                * Record information about a contracts payment method history at a point

Distributed Tracing
            * Every request gets a correlationId at the API Gateway
            * Travels through: HTTP headers, Kafka message headers, log entries
            * MDC in Spring Boot adds it to every log line automatically
            * Search one ID and see full journey across all services
            * Tools: OpenTelemetry

